00:01:47.010 --> 00:01:50.780
Our concept of standards really
comes from industrialization.

00:01:50.780 --> 00:01:55.320
Suddenly we grew amazing
complexity and scale,

00:01:55.320 --> 00:01:57.550
and we realized
pretty quickly-- like,

00:01:57.550 --> 00:02:00.010
snap-- this is really hard.

00:02:00.010 --> 00:02:01.510
We don't really
know how to do this,

00:02:01.510 --> 00:02:03.750
and actually we still don't
really know how to do it.

00:02:03.750 --> 00:02:06.530
But this is the beginning
of professional engineers,

00:02:06.530 --> 00:02:10.280
and these engineering
associations started

00:02:10.280 --> 00:02:14.190
and engineers went, "We need
some controls around the stuff.

00:02:14.190 --> 00:02:15.040
We need standards."

00:02:15.040 --> 00:02:17.690
And so they started, and
they created these standards.

00:02:17.690 --> 00:02:21.556
And they were regional
and incompatible,

00:02:21.556 --> 00:02:23.560
and they found out
some valuable lessons,

00:02:23.560 --> 00:02:26.080
like technically great ideas
that you can't actually

00:02:26.080 --> 00:02:28.390
get implemented--
they're not worth much.

00:02:28.390 --> 00:02:31.000
And at that time, the
physical resource makers

00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:34.032
had veto power, so
they said "No, It's

00:02:34.032 --> 00:02:34.990
going to cost too much.

00:02:34.990 --> 00:02:36.670
We can't do that."

00:02:36.670 --> 00:02:39.997
But as these companies
scaled to ginormous size,

00:02:39.997 --> 00:02:41.830
they learned the value
of internal standards

00:02:41.830 --> 00:02:45.350
and slowly changed their mind
about external standards, too.

00:02:45.350 --> 00:02:47.120
And part of the reason
that was possible

00:02:47.120 --> 00:02:49.240
is because of things
like this: 1903,

00:02:49.240 --> 00:02:53.370
the Great Baltimore Fire
wiped out Baltimore.

00:02:53.370 --> 00:02:56.810
It was a big deal.

00:02:56.810 --> 00:02:59.590
There were over 600 variants
of hose and size couplings,

00:02:59.590 --> 00:03:01.090
so people showed up.

00:03:01.090 --> 00:03:03.140
They weren't painful and rude.

00:03:03.140 --> 00:03:05.830
They showed up, but
they couldn't help.

00:03:05.830 --> 00:03:08.880
So things like this
made it really acutely

00:03:08.880 --> 00:03:11.260
aware to lot of people
that we need standards,

00:03:11.260 --> 00:03:16.170
and so they started in
the UK and then in the US

00:03:16.170 --> 00:03:18.080
we started doing it, too.

00:03:18.080 --> 00:03:20.660
And then, finally, I think
we're getting to the point

00:03:20.660 --> 00:03:22.250
that I'm going to
start on here, which

00:03:22.250 --> 00:03:26.690
is our approach to standards
has changed over time.

00:03:26.690 --> 00:03:30.750
We've tried lots of things,
and every once in awhile we

00:03:30.750 --> 00:03:34.400
need a little revolution
to say, "Hey, you're

00:03:34.400 --> 00:03:36.580
not thinking about
this properly."

00:03:36.580 --> 00:03:40.490
And it's worth learning
from what's happened before,

00:03:40.490 --> 00:03:42.990
too, because pretty
much everything that's

00:03:42.990 --> 00:03:46.010
been waged about standards
that we're saying now

00:03:46.010 --> 00:03:48.430
has been waged in the past.

00:03:48.430 --> 00:03:49.610
And here's what we know.

00:03:49.610 --> 00:03:52.290
We know that standards are
necessary at some level.

00:03:52.290 --> 00:03:54.420
They're really hard.

00:03:54.420 --> 00:03:57.480
And that they're technically
better at the "last miles"

00:03:57.480 --> 00:03:58.430
than the first ones.

00:03:58.430 --> 00:04:01.260
They're not the greatest
source of innovation,

00:04:01.260 --> 00:04:03.130
but they're really
the only ones that

00:04:03.130 --> 00:04:06.650
are capable of crossing
the boundary to,

00:04:06.650 --> 00:04:09.230
this is really a standard.

00:04:09.230 --> 00:04:12.160
But I'm emphasizing
this: they're

00:04:12.160 --> 00:04:15.490
trying to solve problems that
are actually fluid, right?

00:04:15.490 --> 00:04:17.940
Environments aren't
a stasis, right?

00:04:17.940 --> 00:04:19.870
And in the '60s, things changed.

00:04:19.870 --> 00:04:24.840
IBM became this giant monolith
and everything was theirs.

00:04:24.840 --> 00:04:26.604
But software changed
the game and got

00:04:26.604 --> 00:04:29.020
us thinking about how to solve
a problem at higher levels.

00:04:32.470 --> 00:04:34.990
Here's two things I want
to compare and contrast,

00:04:34.990 --> 00:04:41.960
is the thing on your left is
EDI, and it was really popular.

00:04:41.960 --> 00:04:44.490
If you wanted to do business
in the '80s you better do this.

00:04:44.490 --> 00:04:47.270
But it's really brittle
and it's really specific,

00:04:47.270 --> 00:04:50.920
and there's no way
that you can do cats,

00:04:50.920 --> 00:04:52.760
It doesn't support cats.

00:04:52.760 --> 00:04:54.810
But this thing on
the other side,

00:04:54.810 --> 00:04:59.090
this is intellectually driven by
a small group at Cambridge IBM

00:04:59.090 --> 00:05:01.190
and it was nurtured.

00:05:01.190 --> 00:05:04.175
And then, when they kind
of had it figured out

00:05:04.175 --> 00:05:05.800
and it computed a
little bit, then they

00:05:05.800 --> 00:05:07.120
put it through standards.

00:05:07.120 --> 00:05:08.850
And it's a really
generalized model,

00:05:08.850 --> 00:05:12.680
and that means that
people can do new things.

00:05:12.680 --> 00:05:15.370
Somebody came along and said,
"You know what the web needs?

00:05:15.370 --> 00:05:18.790
Kittens."

00:05:18.790 --> 00:05:21.425
Same thing kind of happened
with network architecture.

00:05:25.650 --> 00:05:28.320
ISO tried to standardize
a network stack,

00:05:28.320 --> 00:05:30.870
and they spent 10
years doing that.

00:05:30.870 --> 00:05:34.620
But meanwhile, somewhere kind of
late through that, [INAUDIBLE]

00:05:34.620 --> 00:05:37.680
and some guys went
to ARPA and they

00:05:37.680 --> 00:05:43.830
focused on a smaller scale of
agreement and running code.

00:05:43.830 --> 00:05:46.610
They got in the door, and
that's why we have the internet.

00:05:46.610 --> 00:05:51.120
So adoption matters, again,
but there's a shift here.

00:05:51.120 --> 00:05:54.330
Now, the makers-- they're
not pushing iron and steel,

00:05:54.330 --> 00:05:58.410
they're pushing bits--
and bits are cheap.

00:05:58.410 --> 00:06:01.100
So then when Tim comes
along-- Tim Burners-Lee

00:06:01.100 --> 00:06:04.130
creates the web--
it's measurably worse

00:06:04.130 --> 00:06:07.150
on a number of access than
a whole bunch of things

00:06:07.150 --> 00:06:09.440
that were available at the time.

00:06:09.440 --> 00:06:12.110
But it had a really, really
little low barrier to entry--

00:06:12.110 --> 00:06:16.380
just view source and you're in.

00:06:16.380 --> 00:06:20.080
And it had enough
to do useful things.

00:06:20.080 --> 00:06:23.670
So it got started, and pretty
soon all those shortcomings

00:06:23.670 --> 00:06:26.610
became evident and we
started to fragment

00:06:26.610 --> 00:06:29.570
and there is this worry
that, "Oh no, now it's

00:06:29.570 --> 00:06:31.170
just going to be chaos."

00:06:31.170 --> 00:06:34.030
So we created the W3C.

00:06:34.030 --> 00:06:36.840
At first there was
really great progress

00:06:36.840 --> 00:06:39.177
because it was "last
mile" sorts of things.

00:06:39.177 --> 00:06:41.510
There were things that already
looked kind of inevitable

00:06:41.510 --> 00:06:45.470
and we just needed a lot of
people to finalize agreement.

00:06:45.470 --> 00:06:49.530
But then we went down
this decade-long foray

00:06:49.530 --> 00:06:56.850
into x-whatever or w-whatever:
XML, XSL, XPath XQuerty.

00:06:56.850 --> 00:06:59.100
Let's just forget it.

00:06:59.100 --> 00:07:01.070
The interesting thing
here is that developers

00:07:01.070 --> 00:07:05.370
became the new veto-power
and important innovators.

00:07:05.370 --> 00:07:09.180
Raise your hand if
you use XML stuff.

00:07:09.180 --> 00:07:11.620
Not much anymore, right?

00:07:11.620 --> 00:07:13.160
It's not what we use.

00:07:13.160 --> 00:07:13.760
We use jQuery.

00:07:16.820 --> 00:07:20.550
We all do use jQuery,
but we use JSON.

00:07:20.550 --> 00:07:27.250
JSON was kind of discovered
but also kind of incubated

00:07:27.250 --> 00:07:30.207
and happened
because we all went,

00:07:30.207 --> 00:07:31.540
good enough, for a lot of stuff.

00:07:34.240 --> 00:07:37.160
These high-level observations:
the technical superiority

00:07:37.160 --> 00:07:38.842
ultimately means little.

00:07:38.842 --> 00:07:40.550
There's all kinds of
different advantages

00:07:40.550 --> 00:07:44.260
that it can trumpet when
we get to standard scale,

00:07:44.260 --> 00:07:46.410
and that software is
a great equalizer.

00:07:46.410 --> 00:07:50.410
It has the potential
to empower developers.

00:07:50.410 --> 00:07:52.970
Standardization in the small
is easier than in the large,

00:07:52.970 --> 00:07:56.550
and when you do it in a small
these adjacent possibles,

00:07:56.550 --> 00:07:57.900
they become possible.

00:07:57.900 --> 00:08:00.409
You build something and somebody
will build on top of it,

00:08:00.409 --> 00:08:01.950
and when they build
on top of it they

00:08:01.950 --> 00:08:03.625
won't do it in a standards body.

00:08:03.625 --> 00:08:05.250
They'll do it out in
the open, and they

00:08:05.250 --> 00:08:08.730
have a little bit more freedom
to make harder decisions

00:08:08.730 --> 00:08:10.350
and get it out
there and compete.

00:08:10.350 --> 00:08:13.650
And eventually,
when we have things

00:08:13.650 --> 00:08:15.510
that start to look
inevitable, we

00:08:15.510 --> 00:08:17.660
can kind of do the
archeology and find out

00:08:17.660 --> 00:08:19.600
where the common
ground is, and then we

00:08:19.600 --> 00:08:21.334
can send that to
a standard's body.

00:08:21.334 --> 00:08:23.000
And if you look at
this from a distance,

00:08:23.000 --> 00:08:26.270
it looks a lot more like a
living system than a machine.

00:08:26.270 --> 00:08:29.360
It looks like
something evolved, not

00:08:29.360 --> 00:08:33.700
something that's
highly, highly designed.

00:08:33.700 --> 00:08:38.510
So here's my point, anyway.

00:08:38.510 --> 00:08:40.710
We have changed
standards in the past,

00:08:40.710 --> 00:08:45.150
and for good reasons when the
little revolution happened,

00:08:45.150 --> 00:08:50.080
and I think it's time
we changed them again.

00:08:50.080 --> 00:08:52.840
So step one is, can
we get everybody

00:08:52.840 --> 00:08:57.040
to agree to some fundamental
principles about what we mean?

00:08:57.040 --> 00:08:59.080
Step one is the
extensible web manifesto,

00:08:59.080 --> 00:09:00.830
where we kind of
articulated, "This

00:09:00.830 --> 00:09:02.590
is what we're talking about.

00:09:02.590 --> 00:09:06.100
Can we get there?"

00:09:06.100 --> 00:09:08.360
If you're not familiar
with it, there's

00:09:08.360 --> 00:09:12.080
just a couple points in it that
I think are really important.

00:09:12.080 --> 00:09:14.650
If we focus on new ideas
and standards bodies,

00:09:14.650 --> 00:09:16.770
we should start with primitives.

00:09:16.770 --> 00:09:20.120
Don't start with these very,
very high declarative things.

00:09:20.120 --> 00:09:22.170
Let's start low
and let's build up

00:09:22.170 --> 00:09:25.480
