00:13:08.190 --> 00:13:12.650
at Adobe in the standards
bodies, and I quit in a year

00:13:12.650 --> 00:13:16.430
and I moved to some other stuff.

00:13:16.430 --> 00:13:18.700
And one of the reason's
is this-- wasting time,

00:13:18.700 --> 00:13:20.402
because there's a
lot of waste of time

00:13:20.402 --> 00:13:21.860
that happens with
standards bodies.

00:13:21.860 --> 00:13:24.650
And Adobe, we pursue
a lot of features.

00:13:24.650 --> 00:13:28.360
We pursue blend modes, and
blend modes are really awesome,

00:13:28.360 --> 00:13:29.930
cool things that's
going to happen.

00:13:29.930 --> 00:13:31.263
It's going to happen soon, guys.

00:13:31.263 --> 00:13:33.040
It's happening.

00:13:33.040 --> 00:13:35.700
And then there is this
[INAUDIBLE] shapes.

00:13:35.700 --> 00:13:36.880
We worked on regions.

00:13:36.880 --> 00:13:39.130
We spent at least
three years on regions,

00:13:39.130 --> 00:13:42.090
which Google said, "Well,
screw your three years of work.

00:13:42.090 --> 00:13:42.930
Too bad."

00:13:42.930 --> 00:13:45.820
And then we did all
of our other stuff,

00:13:45.820 --> 00:13:47.290
so there's a lot
of waste of time.

00:13:47.290 --> 00:13:50.290
And I think this is very
important discussion to have.

00:13:50.290 --> 00:13:53.340
And a lot of waste of time
happens in the mailing list

00:13:53.340 --> 00:13:55.757
and in the weekly meetings.

00:13:55.757 --> 00:13:57.590
And a lot of time it
happens because there's

00:13:57.590 --> 00:14:00.900
somebody who has a lot of
time that you don't, and they

00:14:00.900 --> 00:14:02.680
would be saying
something like, "I

00:14:02.680 --> 00:14:04.530
don't agree with this
particular syntax.

00:14:04.530 --> 00:14:07.472
It should have a bubble
or another digit,"

00:14:07.472 --> 00:14:08.430
or something like that.

00:14:08.430 --> 00:14:11.690
You don't have time to waste
to apply to such nonsense

00:14:11.690 --> 00:14:14.530
but you have to, because
otherwise your proposal will

00:14:14.530 --> 00:14:15.880
not get accepted.

00:14:15.880 --> 00:14:19.970
So do you waste
time there or do you

00:14:19.970 --> 00:14:21.960
do things that are interesting?

00:14:21.960 --> 00:14:23.354
You have to decide.

00:14:23.354 --> 00:14:25.270
And that's where most
of the time gets wasted.

00:14:25.270 --> 00:14:26.728
LYZA GARDNER: What
you think, Alex?

00:14:26.728 --> 00:14:28.440
I can sort of see you
squirming a touch.

00:14:28.440 --> 00:14:30.398
ALEX RUSSELL: Well, I'm
squirming in agreement.

00:14:32.560 --> 00:14:37.080
For background, my
most recent experience

00:14:37.080 --> 00:14:40.410
with the pain of
Divya's is expressing

00:14:40.410 --> 00:14:43.760
came with the promises
spec in [INAUDIBLE].

00:14:43.760 --> 00:14:48.740
So we, in 2013 in
probably February,

00:14:48.740 --> 00:14:50.857
had a thing that hung
together, and we sort of

00:14:50.857 --> 00:14:51.690
had agreement on it.

00:14:51.690 --> 00:14:55.690
The March meeting of 2013
we thought we had general

00:14:55.690 --> 00:14:58.312
agreement about sort of a
cut-down version of an overall

00:14:58.312 --> 00:15:00.520
promises thing that was A+
compatible that we'd spent

00:15:00.520 --> 00:15:03.710
a bunch of time working with
stakeholders to get done.

00:15:03.710 --> 00:15:09.190
Anyway, I'm going to fast
forward to early 2014.

00:15:09.190 --> 00:15:12.030
Early this year we had yet
another series of flareups

00:15:12.030 --> 00:15:16.140
after wasting something like
another six or eight months

00:15:16.140 --> 00:15:18.960
on inconsequential debate to
try to get something done,

00:15:18.960 --> 00:15:21.010
and largely-- heroically--
brought over the line

00:15:21.010 --> 00:15:22.540
by Dominic.

00:15:22.540 --> 00:15:24.589
He sort of picked
up the ball after I

00:15:24.589 --> 00:15:25.630
rage-quit on the process.

00:15:28.830 --> 00:15:31.350
This speaks to, on the one
hand, the exact dynamics

00:15:31.350 --> 00:15:33.460
you're talking about,
about requiring

00:15:33.460 --> 00:15:39.670
the notion of consensus
without getting something

00:15:39.670 --> 00:15:41.510
valuable in people's hands.

00:15:41.510 --> 00:15:43.316
Promises should have
been a slam dunk.

00:15:43.316 --> 00:15:45.690
Promises should have been the
easiest thing in the world,

00:15:45.690 --> 00:15:47.765
because every Javascript
library on the planet

00:15:47.765 --> 00:15:49.390
has something that
looks like Promises.

00:15:49.390 --> 00:15:51.514
And in fact, when we started
this design exercise--

00:15:51.514 --> 00:15:53.846
Jake and [INAUDIBLE] and
I, with Dominic's help

00:15:53.846 --> 00:15:55.220
and [? Mark Millan's ?]
help-- we

00:15:55.220 --> 00:15:57.940
sort of went through
all of the catalogue

00:15:57.940 --> 00:16:00.000
of the popular Promises
libraries and all

00:16:00.000 --> 00:16:02.670
the antecedents and of the
cross-language comparisons

00:16:02.670 --> 00:16:05.500
and tried to come up with
something that looked good

00:16:05.500 --> 00:16:08.160
and extract the common
core out of this.

00:16:08.160 --> 00:16:10.590
And yet, everyone
has an opinion.

00:16:10.590 --> 00:16:14.220
It's not clear that
those standards processes

00:16:14.220 --> 00:16:18.340
that require consensus
are necessarily

00:16:18.340 --> 00:16:19.472
the way to make progress.

00:16:19.472 --> 00:16:21.930
It would be better if we can
make progress through science.

00:16:21.930 --> 00:16:23.513
We can go and we can
look at the world

00:16:23.513 --> 00:16:25.610
and figure out who's
doing the most of what

00:16:25.610 --> 00:16:29.120
and see what deserves to be
written down in the dictionary.

00:16:29.120 --> 00:16:31.350
I sort of think of it
like slang in dictionary.

00:16:31.350 --> 00:16:34.540
We grow slang, just
the way we pick up

00:16:34.540 --> 00:16:36.430
a word then toss it out.

00:16:36.430 --> 00:16:37.920
But if it's really
popular it gets

00:16:37.920 --> 00:16:38.880
written into the dictionary.

00:16:38.880 --> 00:16:40.920
LYZA GARDNER: Am I hearing that
there's too much consensus,

00:16:40.920 --> 00:16:42.250
or is it that the questions--

00:16:42.250 --> 00:16:42.720
ADRIAN BATEMAN:
Too much consensus?

00:16:42.720 --> 00:16:45.290
LYZA GARDNER: Or, too much
reliance on consensus.

00:16:45.290 --> 00:16:48.880
Or is it that the discussion
points are too broad?

00:16:48.880 --> 00:16:53.047
ADRIAN BATEMAN: No, I think
the problem is who decides.

00:16:53.047 --> 00:16:54.630
LYZA GARDNER: Who
should be consulted?

00:16:54.630 --> 00:16:57.560
ADRIAN BATEMAN: Who should
be in charge of this?

00:16:57.560 --> 00:17:00.000
Consensus means that everybody
gets to say something.

00:17:00.000 --> 00:17:02.840
And as Alex said,
everybody has an opinion.

00:17:02.840 --> 00:17:04.490
The reason these
things take forever

00:17:04.490 --> 00:17:06.490
is because everybody
wants their say.

00:17:06.490 --> 00:17:10.839
Everybody wants to put their
little stamp on the speck.

00:17:10.839 --> 00:17:13.790
In the absence of that, if
we want to do something else,

00:17:13.790 --> 00:17:16.440
then how do we decide who's
going to be in charge?

00:17:16.440 --> 00:17:19.420
LYZA GARDNER: How do
we short circuit that?

00:17:19.420 --> 00:17:20.380
What's an alternative?

00:17:20.380 --> 00:17:22.380
ADRIAN BATEMAN: Do we
just go into a closed room

00:17:22.380 --> 00:17:24.849
and say, you to
pay to get in here,

00:17:24.849 --> 00:17:28.040
or you have to pass some
test to get in here,

00:17:28.040 --> 00:17:30.200
or you have to solve some
riddle to get in here.

00:17:30.200 --> 00:17:30.570
How do you do that?

00:17:30.570 --> 00:17:31.770
ALEX RUSSELL: Let
me just suggest

00:17:31.770 --> 00:17:33.610
that I think of the worst
things that we've ever

00:17:33.610 --> 00:17:34.970
done as a series
of communities--

00:17:34.970 --> 00:17:37.136
because it's not just one
place-- we don't talk very

00:17:37.136 --> 00:17:41.000
much, and that's another
topic for debate here,

00:17:41.000 --> 00:17:43.509
despite talking too
much on mailing lists.

00:17:43.509 --> 00:17:45.800
Mailing lists are the worst
form of human communication

00:17:45.800 --> 00:17:48.420
yet invented.

00:17:48.420 --> 00:17:51.531
I submit this for challenge.

00:17:51.531 --> 00:17:53.530
LYZA GARDNER: How do you
think would be a better

00:17:53.530 --> 00:17:55.560
alternative for people to
communicate about these things?

00:17:55.560 --> 00:17:57.893
ALEX RUSSELL: I think that
when these processes go well,

00:17:57.893 --> 00:17:59.900
we do it by creating small
communities of people

00:17:59.900 --> 00:18:03.050
who are both informed and
invested in the topics,

00:18:03.050 --> 00:18:04.740
because the larger
community is going

00:18:04.740 --> 00:18:06.698
to be able to take signals
about whether or not

00:18:06.698 --> 00:18:08.292
something is healthy
from experts.

00:18:08.292 --> 00:18:10.250
Not everybody is an
expert, and maybe everybody

00:18:10.250 --> 00:18:13.100
does have an opinion, but
getting those opinions

00:18:13.100 --> 00:18:15.500
from an opinion to
an informed opinion

00:18:15.500 --> 00:18:17.700
generally requires that
people read up on things.

00:18:17.700 --> 00:18:22.120
To do that, you often want to
build from a small set of tests

00:18:22.120 --> 00:18:24.710
about an idea, and hopefully
there's competition.

00:18:24.710 --> 00:18:30.920
But once that first primordial
set of evolutions happens,

00:18:30.920 --> 00:18:32.740
you can start to grow
the group of people

00:18:32.740 --> 00:18:36.876
who are invested and involved,
if the platform supports it.

00:18:36.876 --> 00:18:38.250
We have this
challenge in a bunch

00:18:38.250 --> 00:18:40.480
of places where
Promises are easy.

00:18:40.480 --> 00:18:43.080
And I kept saying that
the only goal for Promises

00:18:43.080 --> 00:18:45.570
is that there was a spec,
because the version that we

00:18:45.570 --> 00:18:48.720
have now isn't good.

00:18:48.720 --> 00:18:52.060
Flat-out has tons
of missing features.

00:18:52.060 --> 00:18:54.500
It's not great,
and its large value

00:18:54.500 --> 00:18:58.650
is that it is the one thing
that you can call Promises.

00:18:58.650 --> 00:19:01.470
That is the place where
standards provide value,

00:19:01.470 --> 00:19:03.620
is that we then can all
agree that it's the thing.

00:19:03.620 --> 00:19:06.000
So you sort of have to thread
the needle to get there,

00:19:06.000 --> 00:19:09.570
but getting that early evolution
going without requiring that

00:19:09.570 --> 00:19:12.990
you boil an entire 2,000-person
mailing list of ideas before

00:19:12.990 --> 00:19:16.330
anyone will start any debate
on anything is really a recipe

00:19:16.330 --> 00:19:17.210
for failure.

00:19:17.210 --> 00:19:18.668
We've been
experimenting with using

00:19:18.668 --> 00:19:20.020
Git Hub to build new things.

00:19:20.020 --> 00:19:21.020
That's only one attempt.

