00:21:58.525 --> 00:22:00.150
AUDIENCE: One of the
comments that Alex

00:22:00.150 --> 00:22:02.810
made was that having a
small group of people that

00:22:02.810 --> 00:22:07.560
are actually informed is
extremely important to find

00:22:07.560 --> 00:22:11.170
a right-size group with
the right set of people.

00:22:11.170 --> 00:22:14.490
We have two extremes,
for example.

00:22:14.490 --> 00:22:17.530
[INAUDIBLE] who does
the [INAUDIBLE] version

00:22:17.530 --> 00:22:20.690
of HTML, who many times
sort of goes alone.

00:22:20.690 --> 00:22:24.970
At least, this is the
impression that I have.

00:22:24.970 --> 00:22:27.900
I guess I should just
speak for myself.

00:22:27.900 --> 00:22:31.910
Basically the working mode
there is generally the editor

00:22:31.910 --> 00:22:32.410
decides.

00:22:32.410 --> 00:22:34.034
He tries to collect
as much information

00:22:34.034 --> 00:22:37.050
to make a scientifically
correct decision.

00:22:37.050 --> 00:22:40.040
And then on the other side, we
have actually, funnily enough,

00:22:40.040 --> 00:22:43.710
the same specification in
the W3C space, where there's

00:22:43.710 --> 00:22:48.570
a mailing list of hundreds
of people and everyone

00:22:48.570 --> 00:22:54.480
opines about every single
thing, and every opinion

00:22:54.480 --> 00:22:57.450
is expressed with
extremely little data:

00:22:57.450 --> 00:23:01.030
"This is my experience having
written this one website,

00:23:01.030 --> 00:23:04.290
and I want a feature that
implements my whole website

00:23:04.290 --> 00:23:07.390
in a single tag."

00:23:07.390 --> 00:23:10.620
