have been happening

00:26:20.780 --> 00:26:23.725
that can help Service Worker be
more successful than AppCache

00:26:23.725 --> 00:26:25.000
was?

00:26:25.000 --> 00:26:27.640
ALEX RUSSELL: Well, I want
to start by giving credit

00:26:27.640 --> 00:26:30.380
to Andrew Betts
and Jake Archibald

00:26:30.380 --> 00:26:34.292
for getting the process
started that has ended up

00:26:34.292 --> 00:26:36.000
at a place where
Service Worker's getting

00:26:36.000 --> 00:26:38.975
implemented quite broadly.

00:26:38.975 --> 00:26:40.350
Obviously it's my
feature, so I'm

00:26:40.350 --> 00:26:42.030
going to say it looks great.

00:26:42.030 --> 00:26:44.051
But the process
was fundamentally

00:26:44.051 --> 00:26:46.050
different to the way that
AppCache was designed.

00:26:46.050 --> 00:26:48.175
The history here is that
there was a project called

00:26:48.175 --> 00:26:51.420
Google Gears, which
attempted to flesh out

00:26:51.420 --> 00:26:54.140
some of these ideas in
a hostile environment.

00:26:54.140 --> 00:26:57.600
It had to be a plug-in for
IE, because IE was dead.

00:26:57.600 --> 00:26:59.660
It had to be a
plug-in for Safari

00:26:59.660 --> 00:27:03.200
because there wasn't really much
to be done, and for Firefox.

00:27:03.200 --> 00:27:04.200
And so it was difficult.

00:27:04.200 --> 00:27:05.866
It had to be implemented
multiple times.

00:27:05.866 --> 00:27:07.580
But it came up
with one solution,

00:27:07.580 --> 00:27:10.770
and then it was clear that
Gears was going to die,

00:27:10.770 --> 00:27:12.830
and so one when Chrome
came about it was like,

00:27:12.830 --> 00:27:14.455
"Well, let's get
everything into HTML."

00:27:14.455 --> 00:27:16.310
So there was a
deliberative process

00:27:16.310 --> 00:27:17.970
of writing down what Gears did.

00:27:17.970 --> 00:27:20.860
And AppCache, to
[INAUDIBLE] credit,

00:27:20.860 --> 00:27:23.580
is a coherent way of thinking
about exactly what Gears

00:27:23.580 --> 00:27:26.030
did inside of HTML, without
reexamining whether or not

00:27:26.030 --> 00:27:28.800
it was a good idea
or a bad idea.

00:27:28.800 --> 00:27:33.440
It had the fundamental flaw of
being a very high-level feature

00:27:33.440 --> 00:27:35.220
without any
extensibility whatsoever,

00:27:35.220 --> 00:27:36.710
so that when something
goes wrong with AppCache --

00:27:36.710 --> 00:27:39.070
and much the way when
something goes wrong with CSS,

00:27:39.070 --> 00:27:40.519
it's effectively a closed box.

00:27:40.519 --> 00:27:42.060
You're completely
screwed because you

00:27:42.060 --> 00:27:43.900
have none of the
latent power of any

00:27:43.900 --> 00:27:45.930
of the intermediate
systems in there.

00:27:45.930 --> 00:27:48.380
Think about how an
image is requested.

00:27:48.380 --> 00:27:50.647
An image starts with
an image element,

00:27:50.647 --> 00:27:51.980
and then it goes to the network.

00:27:51.980 --> 00:27:53.060
It fetches some stuff.

00:27:53.060 --> 00:27:54.410
It gets some bytes back.

00:27:54.410 --> 00:27:56.020
It picks an image decoder.

00:27:56.020 --> 00:27:58.220
It decodes it and
it paints them.

00:27:58.220 --> 00:28:00.447
These are all steps
that we can enumerate,

00:28:00.447 --> 00:28:02.780
things that there should be
APIs for, and in some cases,

00:28:02.780 --> 00:28:03.863
there are in the platform.

00:28:03.863 --> 00:28:06.110
But you can plug it
in just a bit of image

00:28:06.110 --> 00:28:08.710
when you want to override,
say, an image format.

00:28:08.710 --> 00:28:11.230
That panel made me nuts.

00:28:11.230 --> 00:28:13.660
We're sitting here thinking
about how Mozilla may or may

00:28:13.660 --> 00:28:16.750
not approach a particular
image format in the future,

00:28:16.750 --> 00:28:19.680
without any data and no
ability whatsoever for us

00:28:19.680 --> 00:28:22.390
as a community to go plug
in our own image decoders,

00:28:22.390 --> 00:28:24.870
despite the fact that
every browser represented

00:28:24.870 --> 00:28:27.730
here has invested
very heavily in ASMJS

00:28:27.730 --> 00:28:29.820
and has workers
with transferables.

00:28:29.820 --> 00:28:32.049
We could be doing image
decoding on our own,

00:28:32.049 --> 00:28:34.590
off-thread, if there was a way
to plumb in our own image data

00:28:34.590 --> 00:28:38.430
the images and just be part of
that image request life cycle.

00:28:38.430 --> 00:28:40.681
It is crazy pants that we
can't be part of that today,

00:28:40.681 --> 00:28:42.763
that we're sitting here
having a debate about what

00:28:42.763 --> 00:28:45.599
browser vendors with a lot of
power are going to do tomorrow.

00:28:45.599 --> 00:28:47.640
That is the goal of the
extensible web manifesto,

00:28:47.640 --> 00:28:49.430
is to get us to a place
where things are layered

00:28:49.430 --> 00:28:50.804
and explained in
such a way where

00:28:50.804 --> 00:28:53.040
and plug-in when you
want some of the power

00:28:53.040 --> 00:28:54.730
or you want to play
inside the framework

00:28:54.730 --> 00:28:56.855
but don't want to have to
reinvent the whole thing.

00:28:56.855 --> 00:28:59.726
LYZA GARDNER: So inaccessibility
is definitely an issue here.

