00:38:43.370 --> 00:38:45.300
or granularity on a low level.

00:38:45.300 --> 00:38:48.600
But APIs like Beacon kind
of fly in the face of that.

00:38:48.600 --> 00:38:50.340
They're higher level.

00:38:50.340 --> 00:38:51.940
Looking at that
API in particular,

00:38:51.940 --> 00:38:54.970
as it's moving forward here,
how would we reconcile that gap?

00:38:54.970 --> 00:38:57.120
What things is it
doing that are in line

00:38:57.120 --> 00:38:59.240
with the tenets
of the manifesto,

00:38:59.240 --> 00:39:02.757
and what things
really differ from it?

00:39:02.757 --> 00:39:04.340
ADRIAN BATEMAN: So
I think the problem

00:39:04.340 --> 00:39:10.070
with taking Beacon and
doing that-- using some

00:39:10.070 --> 00:39:12.050
of these lower
level primitives--

00:39:12.050 --> 00:39:14.760
ultimately comes
down to performance.

00:39:14.760 --> 00:39:18.270
And this is another area that
I worry about with the approach

00:39:18.270 --> 00:39:20.030
of making everything low level.

00:39:20.030 --> 00:39:25.970
So it's true that we could
build the Beacon API, which

00:39:25.970 --> 00:39:31.220
is a way of having a page
send some data to a server,

00:39:31.220 --> 00:39:33.680
even if it's during unload so
you don't have to wait around

00:39:33.680 --> 00:39:35.940
for the response to that.

00:39:35.940 --> 00:39:40.030
It's true that you could build
that using a Service Worker.

00:39:40.030 --> 00:39:43.800
But we have lots of
concerns around the impact

00:39:43.800 --> 00:39:46.940
that Service Worker might have
on the performance of page

00:39:46.940 --> 00:39:47.440
loading.

00:39:47.440 --> 00:39:51.650
We spend a lot of time on
getting pages time to glass

00:39:51.650 --> 00:39:55.470
and the focus on that, and
the counterargument to that

00:39:55.470 --> 00:39:57.820
has always been, "Well,
ServiceWorker is a pay for play

00:39:57.820 --> 00:39:58.320
thing.

00:39:58.320 --> 00:40:01.800
If you want to use ServiceWorker
then when you accept that

00:40:01.800 --> 00:40:03.310
that might have some impact."

00:40:03.310 --> 00:40:06.369
Which is fine except this is
for analytics, Which is probably

00:40:06.369 --> 00:40:08.785
going to be on every page, and
now suddenly have a Service

00:40:08.785 --> 00:40:11.060
Worker on every page
and now every page

00:40:11.060 --> 00:40:12.990
is paying this penalty.

00:40:12.990 --> 00:40:15.510
And I'm not sure that's
the right way to go always,

00:40:15.510 --> 00:40:18.620
and so maybe there's a
place for a simple API.

00:40:18.620 --> 00:40:20.500
This is pretty short
spec that just says,

00:40:20.500 --> 00:40:21.700
"Here's a way of sending--

00:40:21.700 --> 00:40:24.125
LYZA GARDNER: So is this
an example of a spec,

00:40:24.125 --> 00:40:26.890
an API that's concise
enough that it's

00:40:26.890 --> 00:40:28.630
easy to just knock
out and get done?

00:40:28.630 --> 00:40:31.470
Or does it have
conflicts, do you think?

00:40:31.470 --> 00:40:34.640
Brian, do you have
a [INAUDIBLE]?

00:40:34.640 --> 00:40:36.830
BRIAN KARDELL: I
think that we have

00:40:36.830 --> 00:40:40.300
to evaluate these things
on a case by case basis,

00:40:40.300 --> 00:40:43.890
and not everything can be
exposed at the lowest level

00:40:43.890 --> 00:40:44.470
possible.

00:40:44.470 --> 00:40:52.430
And I think that where we
choose to do that is debatable.

00:40:52.430 --> 00:40:53.850
At one point there
was discussion

00:40:53.850 --> 00:40:56.270
about whether we should
have block storage.

00:40:56.270 --> 00:41:01.470
That's really low level and like
nobody writes block storage.

00:41:01.470 --> 00:41:03.720
And some other people said,
