LYZA GARDNER: All right.

00:49:01.410 --> 00:49:03.118
So I want to keep us
moving a little bit.

00:49:03.118 --> 00:49:07.670
Let's shift directions just a
bit right now, in terms of I

00:49:07.670 --> 00:49:10.380
want to talk a little
bit about the gap that

00:49:10.380 --> 00:49:14.290
exists between APIs--
especially device APIs-- exposed

00:49:14.290 --> 00:49:17.760
for Web in browsers versus
that which you have access

00:49:17.760 --> 00:49:19.100
to natively.

00:49:19.100 --> 00:49:21.972
Are there tactics that we can
use-- and some of the stuff

00:49:21.972 --> 00:49:23.930
we haven't talked about--
to move things faster

00:49:23.930 --> 00:49:26.100
to close that gap
a bit, or is always

00:49:26.100 --> 00:49:28.240
going to be a game of catch up?

00:49:28.240 --> 00:49:30.030
And what can we do
about it, if anything?

00:49:32.932 --> 00:49:34.390
KENNETH CHRISTIANSEN:
Well, I think

00:49:34.390 --> 00:49:36.630
we have seen a lot of
progress since we tried

00:49:36.630 --> 00:49:40.610
to make like smaller specs and
solve small use cases instead

00:49:40.610 --> 00:49:42.560
of trying to solve
really big use cases,

00:49:42.560 --> 00:49:44.940
like, "Oh, we're going to
make a Bluetooth API so let's

00:49:44.940 --> 00:49:47.090
solve everything you
could do with Bluetooth."

00:49:47.090 --> 00:49:49.440
No, let's try to solve those
things that people need

00:49:49.440 --> 00:49:51.510
or they really
want here and now.

00:49:51.510 --> 00:49:53.490
Something like the
device orientation lock.

00:49:53.490 --> 00:49:55.840
People want to be able
to lock their screen.

00:49:55.840 --> 00:49:57.720
So it's a very small spec.

00:49:57.720 --> 00:50:01.560
The problem is, I think, the
biggest gap is time to market.

00:50:01.560 --> 00:50:03.660
We need to be quick at
shipping these new things.

00:50:03.660 --> 00:50:05.340
LYZA GARDNER: So
how do we do that?

00:50:05.340 --> 00:50:06.965
Are we still talk
about the same things

00:50:06.965 --> 00:50:10.800
we've been talking
about, like less

00:50:10.800 --> 00:50:13.010
of a net thrown around
huge consensus building.

00:50:13.010 --> 00:50:14.520
Less infighting.

00:50:14.520 --> 00:50:16.501
Fewer people working.

00:50:16.501 --> 00:50:17.750
Are those the kinds of things?

00:50:17.750 --> 00:50:20.507
ALEX RUSSELL: I have a heretical
suggestion, if that's OK.

00:50:20.507 --> 00:50:22.132
LYZA GARDNER: Heretical,
here it comes.

00:50:23.850 --> 00:50:26.266
ALEX RUSSELL: My colleague
Jeff [INAUDIBLE] is at the back

00:50:26.266 --> 00:50:28.230
and he's working on
a Bluetooth spec,

00:50:28.230 --> 00:50:32.460
and Bluetooth is a particularly
terrible and terrifying aspect

00:50:32.460 --> 00:50:34.960
of all of this because it is
very much a hardware spec,

00:50:34.960 --> 00:50:38.070
and you can get things wrong
and you can break devices.

00:50:38.070 --> 00:50:41.020
If you talk at the wrong level,
as Jeff has given me a tour of,

00:50:41.020 --> 00:50:43.204
you can totally brick
devices that you carry around

00:50:43.204 --> 00:50:44.870
in your pocket with
you, and that's bad.

00:50:44.870 --> 00:50:47.510
And exposing that to the
web is clearly dangerous.

00:50:47.510 --> 00:50:49.431
At the same time, we
have a security model.

00:50:49.431 --> 00:50:50.930
It's called the
Origin model, and we

00:50:50.930 --> 00:50:53.410
have a lot of capabilities
that we don't have a way

00:50:53.410 --> 00:50:56.300
to expose today, and the way
we start getting capabilities

00:50:56.300 --> 00:50:58.600
into the web is by
getting everyone in a room

00:50:58.600 --> 00:51:01.040
and going, "Guys,
guys, what's the API?"

00:51:01.040 --> 00:51:03.230
Which has a bunch of
implicit questions about it.

00:51:03.230 --> 00:51:06.740
And that idea of sorting out
the API before you provide

00:51:06.740 --> 00:51:10.240
the capability at some very
low level is quite difficult,

00:51:10.240 --> 00:51:12.510
and so we don't have any
really narrow channels--

00:51:12.510 --> 00:51:14.910
common channels--
to map capabilities

00:51:14.910 --> 00:51:18.510
onto URLs for things which we
don't have a standard for yet.

00:51:18.510 --> 00:51:21.940
And Dmitiri Glaskov who helped
write the original explainer

00:51:21.940 --> 00:51:24.250
document for Web
Components-- which we just

00:51:24.250 --> 00:51:27.484
copied for the Service
Worker, basically--

00:51:27.484 --> 00:51:29.650
he has this idea called
navigator dot connect, which

00:51:29.650 --> 00:51:31.525
is just sort of way of
thinking about mapping

00:51:31.525 --> 00:51:34.650
a bunch of other things into
Service Workers and Origins,

00:51:34.650 --> 00:51:36.674
and maybe that could be
devices on your system.

00:51:36.674 --> 00:51:38.590
Obviously it's up to the
system to mediate it,

00:51:38.590 --> 00:51:40.670
but that's one
possible way forward

00:51:40.670 --> 00:51:42.870
where we have a very,
very, very narrow API

00:51:42.870 --> 00:51:46.715
and it's up to run times to
provide some sort of mapping

00:51:46.715 --> 00:51:48.650
to those capabilities.

00:51:48.650 --> 00:51:53.320
LYZA GARDNER: Jonas

00:51:53.320 --> 00:51:56.700
