00:51:56.700 --> 00:51:58.920
is going to help
with device APIs.

00:51:58.920 --> 00:52:02.000
The main problem we have
with device APIs is security.

00:52:02.000 --> 00:52:04.290
We just don't know how
to expose certain things

00:52:04.290 --> 00:52:06.416
to the web, given the web's
current security model.

00:52:06.416 --> 00:52:09.040
LYZA GARDNER: So device APIs are
sort of special in this sense?

00:52:09.040 --> 00:52:09.600
They don't--

00:52:09.600 --> 00:52:11.430
JONAS: Well, yes, in a sense.

00:52:11.430 --> 00:52:13.086
There's more things
than device APIs

00:52:13.086 --> 00:52:14.960
that are limited by
security, but that that's

00:52:14.960 --> 00:52:16.160
a very good example.

00:52:16.160 --> 00:52:20.220
And I actually think that device
API is a very good example

00:52:20.220 --> 00:52:25.470
of a place where exposing
the low level primitives

00:52:25.470 --> 00:52:27.890
isn't the right thing to do.

00:52:27.890 --> 00:52:31.440
So we've actually had
file access on the web

00:52:31.440 --> 00:52:34.870
for over a decade--
maybe two, even--

00:52:34.870 --> 00:52:36.660
in the form of input
type equals file.

00:52:36.660 --> 00:52:40.690
It's a very terrible
API but it has gotten us

00:52:40.690 --> 00:52:43.250
through these many,
many years and it

00:52:43.250 --> 00:52:46.020
has allowed us to
very powerful things.

00:52:46.020 --> 00:52:49.370
We have yet to figure out
how to expose the low level

00:52:49.370 --> 00:52:52.659
version of that, which is
raw, file level access where

00:52:52.659 --> 00:52:54.575
a website could just
enumerate your hard drive

00:52:54.575 --> 00:52:57.210
and find all the images
and play all your music.

00:52:57.210 --> 00:52:59.260
That'll be super cool
once we figure it out,

00:52:59.260 --> 00:53:01.030
but if that's was
the first thing we

00:53:01.030 --> 00:53:05.350
went to, then we would still
not have a lot of the things

00:53:05.350 --> 00:53:07.949
that we have to today,
like probably not YouTube.

00:53:07.949 --> 00:53:09.740
LYZA GARDNER: So in a
sense, though, you're

00:53:09.740 --> 00:53:13.480
kind of saying that something
low-ish level that was exposed

00:53:13.480 --> 00:53:15.920
has actually been
extremely useful.

00:53:15.920 --> 00:53:19.300
JONAS: It could've
been useful, but if we

00:53:19.300 --> 00:53:24.220
had made that the only
thing we have worked on then

00:53:24.220 --> 00:53:25.590
I think we would have failed.

00:53:25.590 --> 00:53:30.460
And so by going to higher levels
and only doing higher level,

00:53:30.460 --> 00:53:33.490
we were able to at least
move forward a little bit.

00:53:33.490 --> 00:53:34.990
And I agree.

00:53:34.990 --> 00:53:37.320
It's good when we can
do the low level thing,

00:53:37.320 --> 00:53:39.450
but especially when
it comes to security

00:53:39.450 --> 00:53:41.610
you can actually often
solve security problems

00:53:41.610 --> 00:53:43.772
by going to higher level.

00:53:43.772 --> 00:53:45.480
LYZA GARDNER: I want
to hear from Vincent

